html.body: E2F4 module E2F4 associates with two different pocket proteins: p130 in quiescent cells and p107 in proliferating cells. In complex, E2F4 is translocated to the nucleus where it repress transcription during G0 and G1 phases (PMID:9372959). Once in the nucleus, the complex binds to DNA and recruits some co-repressors of transcription: the chromatin remodeler Sin3B, the deacetylase histone HDAC1 and the methyltransferase histones SUV39H1 (PMID:15769944; PMID:11959842). At the G0/G1 transition, when the quiescent cells receive signals from growth factors, p130 starts to be phosphorylated and dissociats from E2F4/DP2. Later, p130 can also be phosphorylated by CycD1/CDK4,6 and CycE1/CDK2 when present and degraded in late G1. It is then replaced by p107 (PMID:12006580). When E2F4/DP2 is in complex with p107, it continues to repress transcription of target genes until it is phosphorylated by CycD1/CDK4,6. E2F4 is then translocated to the cytoplasm, relieving its repression activity whereas both p130 and p107 are able to inhibit CycE1/CDK2 and CycA2/CDK2 activities (PMID:15456871).
